## 1 Overview
In this lesson you will learn how to use two shift registers and how to control a 4 Digit 7 Segment with Common Cathode display.

## 3 Component Introduction

### 4 Digit 7 Segment with Common Cathode display

This display is made from 4 digits and has 7 segments, meaning that it is
made up of 7 LEDs to represent a digit from 0Î© resistor; to 9 when the 7 LEDs are turned on in
a specific manner. Also, it has an 8 th LED for the dot (decimal point). This display is
with common cathode, which means that the cathode is common for the 8 LEDs of
each digit. Below you can find two schemes for the display to understand the linking
between LEDs and the 12 pins.

Each digit has 7 LEDs plus 1 LED for the dot, named from A to G, and DP for
the dot. The anode for the four digits is common, and the cathode for all LEDs of each
digit is common, as shown in the scheme above. We have 12 pins, 8 for the letters A â
G and DP (these are anodes connected to digital pins on the development board), and
we have 4 pins (also called the digit pins) for the cathode of each digit (12, 9, 8 and 6).

## 5 Code

The A (also B â G and DP) LEDs have common anode for all 4 digits,
meaning that if we connect all 4 digit pins to the ground, and the A pin to 3.3V the A
LEDs will light up on all 4 digits.

The code starts by importing the libraries used, declaring the pins used by the
shift registers and set them as OUTPUT. These pins also needs to be initialized with
LOW. Next, we have created some byte variables whose values have set to HIGH
only one bit that corresponds to an output pin of the shift register. For example, we
have the a variable that has the 0b00000001 value. When we will send this value to
the shift register only the Q A is set to HIGH. To this output is connected the 11 pin
of the 4 Digit 7 Segment Display, and this pin is for the A LEDs that will light up
after sending the a value to the shift register.

If we wand to display a number form 0 to 9, we have to turn some of the
segments on and leave the rest to off. For example, if we want to display a 0, we have
to turn on the A, B, C, D, E, F segments. For this, we need to turn on a specific digit
and send to the first shift register the next value 0b00111111. We also have the
variant with the dots turned on 0b10111111. So, for each number we need 2
variables, with and without the dot turned on.

We need a variable to tell us which digits of the display are turned on and
which are turned off. A function created for this code is Digit(x) and contains if elif
statements that will update the value of the digit variable, depending on the value of
the x parameter. You can notice that we give to the digit variable integer values, but
you can find the value written as 8 bits commented next to the integer value.

Our shift() function is a little different. The buffer given as parameter will
contain the variable to turn on/off the segments. The digit variable will be made
visible in this function by telling that we are working with a global variable. Now,
we will send the 8 bits variable that deals with the digits and then send the value for
buffer, which deals with the segments.

In the while True loop we will select all the digits to be turned on and then
send the eight 8 bits variables, created at the beginning of the code, one after another
at a interval of 1000 ms. After this, you will see that every segment and the decimal
point will light up.

Further, we will select only the first digit to be turnd on and set the A
segment to HIGH. After this, all the digits will be selected and a 0 will appear on all
of them, with the dot turned off.

In the last part of the while True loop the first digit will be selected and on it
will be displayed a 1, then the second digit will be selected and on it will be displayed
2. Next, on the third digit will be displayed a 3 and on the fourth digit will be
displayed a 4.

"""
 * Credits: www.plusivo.com
 *
 * Lesson 29: 4 Digit 7 Segment Display
 *
 * The code below is created for the lesson "4 Digit 7 Segment Display",
 * where you will learn how to use multiple shift registers
 * to control each digit and LED of the included display.
 *
 * Make sure you made the right connections and connected the cables
 * in the order showed in the guide.
 *
 * More details can be found in the guide.
"""

#we import the RPi.GPIO library with the name of GPIO
import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import time

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BOARD)

#declare the pins used by the shift registers
dataPin = 12
latchPin = 10
clockPin = 8

#set all the pins as OUTPUT
GPIO.setup(dataPin, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(latchPin, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(clockPin, GPIO.OUT)

#set the initial state for the pins as LOW
GPIO.output(dataPin, GPIO.LOW)
GPIO.output(latchPin, GPIO.LOW)
GPIO.output(clockPin, GPIO.LOW)

#create byte variables that have only one segment set to HIGH
a = 0b00000001
b = 0b00000010
c = 0b00000100
d = 0b00001000
e = 0b00010000
f = 0b00100000
g = 0b01000000
dot = 0b10000000

zero = 191         #0b10111111
zero_no_dot = 63   #0b00111111
one = 134          #0b10000110
one_no_dot = 6     #0b00000110
two = 219          #0b11011011
two_no_dot = 91    #0b01011011
three = 207        #0b11001111
three_no_dot = 79  #0b01001111
four = 230         #0b11100110
four_no_dot = 102  #0b01100110
five = 237         #0b11101101
five_no_dot = 109  #0b01101101
six = 253          #0b11111101
six_no_dot = 125   #0b01111101
seven = 135        #0b10000111
seven_no_dot = 7   #0b00000111
eight = 255        #0b11111111
eight_no_dot = 127 #0b01111111
nine = 239         #0b11101111
nine_no_dot = 111  #0b01101111


def Digit(x):
    global digit
    if x == 1:
        digit = 14 #0b00001110
    elif x == 2:
        digit = 13 #0b00001101
    elif x == 3:
        digit = 11 #0b00001011
    elif x == 4:
        digit = 7 #0b00000111
    elif x == 5:
        digit = 0 #0b00000000

def shift(buffer):
    #make the global variable available
    global digit

    #send the bits to the second shift register
    for i in range(0,8):
        GPIO.output(dataPin, (128 & (digit << i)))
        GPIO.output(clockPin, GPIO.HIGH)
        time.sleep(0.001)
        GPIO.output(clockPin, GPIO.LOW)

    #send the bits to the first shift register
    for i in range(0,8):
        GPIO.output(dataPin, (128 & (buffer << i)))
        GPIO.output(clockPin, GPIO.HIGH)
        time.sleep(0.001)
        GPIO.output(clockPin, GPIO.LOW)

    #shift the bits
    GPIO.output(latchPin, GPIO.HIGH)
    time.sleep(0.001)
    GPIO.output(latchPin, GPIO.LOW)
try:
    while True:
            Digit(5)

            #send two byte values tothe shift registers
            #after this, all the A LEDs will turn on, because
            #all the digits are turned on (they are set to LOW)
            shift(a)
            time.sleep(1)

            #turn on all the B LEDs
            shift(b)
            time.sleep(1)

            #turn on all the C LEDs
            shift(c)
            time.sleep(1)

            #turn on all the D LEDs
            shift(d)
            time.sleep(1)

            #turn on all the E LEDs
            shift(e)
            time.sleep(1)

            #turn on all the F LEDs
            shift(f)
            time.sleep(1)

            #turn on all the G LEDs
            shift(g)
            time.sleep(1)

            #turn on the LEDs for the dots
            shift(dot)
            time.sleep(1)


         #select the first digit
            Digit(1)

            #turn on the A LED on the selected digit
            shift(a)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select all digits
            Digit(5)
            #display on the selected digits a "0"
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned off
            shift(zero_no_dot)
            time.sleep(1)

                #select the first and display on it a "1" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(1)
            shift(one)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select the first and display on it a "2" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(2)
            shift(two)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select the first and display on it a "3" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(3)
            shift(three)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select the first and display on it a "4" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(4)
            shift(four)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select the first and display on it a "5" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(5)
            shift(five)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select the first and display on it a "6" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(6)
            shift(six)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select the first and display on it a "7" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(7)
            shift(seven)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select the first and display on it a "8" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(8)
            shift(eight)
            time.sleep(1)

            #select the first and display on it a "9" for 1 s
            #the LEDs for the dots are turned on
            Digit(9)
            shift(nine)
            time.sleep(1)

except KeyboardInterrupt:
    pass
digit = 0
shift(0)
GPIO.cleanup()
